        <article id="fruitsandvegetables">
            <h3>Fruits and Vegetables</h3>
            <p>Fruits come from the flowering part of a plant and contain seeds, while vegetables are the edible parts of a plant, such as the leaves, roots, stems, or bulbs. They are a good source of vitamins, minerals, fiber, antioxidants, and plant compounds. They are also usually low in fat and sodium.A diet high in fruits and vegetables can help reduce the risk of serious health problems, such as heart disease, stroke, type 2 diabetes, obesity, and some cancers.The Department of Agriculture recommends that adults consume 1.5 to 2.5 cups of fruit and 2 to 4 cups of vegetables per day.</p>
        </article>
    <main>
        <article id="grains">
            <h3>Grains</h3>
            <p>Grains are seeds or fruits from cereal grasses, also known as kernels. They are a key part of the human diet and have been cultivated for thousands of years.</p>
            <p>Grains are a great source of nutrients, including: 
                Fiber: Helps lower the risk of heart disease, stroke, and type 2 diabetes 
                B vitamins: Help the body release energy from food and are important for a healthy nervous system 
                Iron: Helps carry oxygen in the blood 
                Magnesium: Helps build bones and release energy from muscles 
                Selenium: Protects cells from oxidation and is important for a healthy immune system </p>

        </article>
